---
import ToolLayout from '../../layouts/ToolLayout.astro';
const title = 'Fabric Waste & Overrun Calculator';
const description = 'Calculate fabric waste percentage from marker efficiency, and how much extra fabric (overrun) to order to cover it.';
const intro = 'Calculate expected fabric waste and how much overrun fabric to order to cover it.';
const category = { id: 'clothing', name: 'Clothing & Garment Tools' };
const faqs = [
  { q: 'What is fabric waste percentage?', a: 'The portion of purchased fabric that doesn\'t end up in a finished garment — lost to the gaps between pattern pieces on the cutting marker, fabric flaws, and end-of-roll losses. It\'s expressed as a percentage of total fabric purchased.' },
  { q: 'What is a typical waste percentage for garment cutting?', a: 'Marker efficiency (the inverse of waste) typically runs 75-90% for standard garment cutting, meaning roughly 10-25% waste, depending on the garment\'s pattern complexity, fabric width, and whether the print/nap requires directional cutting.' },
  { q: 'What is overrun in fabric purchasing?', a: 'Overrun is the extra fabric ordered on top of the theoretical exact-yield amount to cover the expected waste percentage plus a buffer for flaws and cutting errors, ensuring the factory doesn\'t run short mid-production.' },
  { q: 'How is overrun different from safety stock?', a: 'Overrun covers the fabric consumed by normal cutting waste on the planned order; safety stock is separate extra inventory held in case of unexpected reorders, quality issues, or replenishment needs beyond the current production run.' },
];
const howTo = {
  name: 'How to calculate fabric waste and overrun',
  steps: [
    { name: 'Enter theoretical fabric needed', text: 'The exact fabric amount for the garment with zero waste (pattern area only).' },
    { name: 'Enter expected waste percentage', text: 'From marker efficiency or historical factory data.' },
    { name: 'Read total fabric to order', text: 'The theoretical amount plus overrun needed to cover waste.' },
  ],
};
---

<ToolLayout title={title} description={description} intro={intro} category={category} faqs={faqs} howTo={howTo}>
  <div class="mt-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4 shadow-sm sm:p-6">
    <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
      <label class="block"><span class="text-sm font-medium text-slate-700">Theoretical fabric needed (m)</span>
        <input id="theoretical" type="number" step="any" placeholder="e.g. 1500" class="mt-1 w-full rounded-xl border border-slate-300 p-3 outline-none focus:border-rose-400 focus:ring-2 focus:ring-rose-100" /></label>
      <label class="block"><span class="text-sm font-medium text-slate-700">Expected waste (%)</span>
        <input id="waste" type="number" step="any" placeholder="e.g. 15" class="mt-1 w-full rounded-xl border border-slate-300 p-3 outline-none focus:border-rose-400 focus:ring-2 focus:ring-rose-100" /></label>
    </div>
    <div id="results" class="mt-6 hidden grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="rounded-xl bg-rose-600 p-5 text-center text-white"><div class="text-sm opacity-80">Total fabric to order</div><div id="r-total" class="mt-1 text-2xl font-bold">—</div></div>
      <div class="rounded-xl bg-slate-50 p-5 text-center"><div class="text-sm text-slate-500">Overrun (extra fabric)</div><div id="r-overrun" class="mt-1 text-2xl font-bold text-slate-800">—</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">How fabric waste and overrun are calculated</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">
      If the theoretical fabric needed with perfect zero-waste cutting is <em>T</em>, and expected waste is a percentage <em>w</em>, then the total fabric to order is <span class="font-mono">T ÷ (1 − w)</span> — not simply <span class="font-mono">T × (1 + w)</span>, which is a common miscalculation. Waste percentage describes what fraction of the fabric bought is lost, so it needs to come out of a larger purchased total, not be added on top of the theoretical figure directly.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600">
      The difference between the two approaches grows with the waste percentage: at 15% waste the two methods differ by only about 2.6%, but at 30% waste they diverge by over 7%, enough to genuinely under-order fabric and stall production if the wrong formula is used. This calculator uses the correct division-based method throughout.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-slate-400">Overrun = theoretical ÷ (1 − waste%) follows standard fabric-procurement and cut-order-planning methodology.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Worked example</h2>
    <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-5">
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-600">A production run needs 1,500 m theoretical fabric at 15% expected waste.</p>
      <div class="mt-2 grid gap-1 text-sm sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Theoretical:</span> <span class="text-slate-600">1,500 m</span></div>
        <div><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Total to order:</span> <span class="text-slate-600">1500 ÷ (1 − 0.15) ≈ <strong>1,764.7 m</strong></span></div>
        <div><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Overrun:</span> <span class="text-slate-600">1764.7 − 1500 ≈ <strong>264.7 m</strong></span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Real-world context</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">
      Under-ordering fabric because of the "add waste on top" miscalculation is a costly, recurring production-planning mistake: a factory that runs short mid-cut has to source a rush top-up order, which frequently means paying a higher spot-market fabric price and risking a dye-lot mismatch between the original and reorder fabric — a visible, quality-affecting problem in a finished garment run.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600">
      Sustainable and low-waste fashion design increasingly focuses on marker-efficient pattern design specifically to shrink this waste percentage at the source — some zero-waste pattern-cutting techniques aim for close to 0% fabric waste by designing pattern pieces that tessellate perfectly, rather than accepting a standard 15-25% loss as unavoidable.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Common misconceptions</h2>
    <div class="mt-3 space-y-3">
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4">
        <p class="text-slate-600">"Adding the waste percentage directly to the theoretical amount is correct." <strong class="text-slate-900">It slightly under-orders.</strong> Dividing by (1 − waste%) correctly accounts for the fact that waste is a share of the total purchased, not just an addition to the theoretical figure.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4">
        <p class="text-slate-600">"All garments have roughly the same waste percentage." <strong class="text-slate-900">It varies a lot.</strong> Simple rectangular pattern pieces waste far less than curved, fitted, or directional-print designs — waste percentage should be estimated per style, not assumed universally.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Related tools</h2>
    <div class="mt-3 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="/tools/fabric-yield-calculator" class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-slate-700 transition hover:border-rose-300 hover:bg-rose-50">Fabric Yield Calculator</a>
      <a href="/tools/fabric-consumption-cost-calculator" class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-slate-700 transition hover:border-rose-300 hover:bg-rose-50">Fabric Consumption-to-Cost Calculator</a>
      <a href="/tools/fabric-shrinkage-calculator" class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-slate-700 transition hover:border-rose-300 hover:bg-rose-50">Fabric Shrinkage Calculator</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <script is:inline>
    const el = (id) => document.getElementById(id);

    function update() {
      const theoretical = parseFloat(el('theoretical').value);
      const waste = parseFloat(el('waste').value);
      if (!(theoretical > 0 && waste >= 0 && waste < 100)) { el('results').classList.add('hidden'); return; }
      const total = theoretical / (1 - waste / 100);
      const overrun = total - theoretical;

      el('r-total').textContent = total.toFixed(1) + ' m';
      el('r-overrun').textContent = '+' + overrun.toFixed(1) + ' m';
      el('results').classList.remove('hidden');
    }

    ['theoretical', 'waste'].forEach((id) => el(id).addEventListener('input', update));
  </script>
</ToolLayout>
